{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_cartier_ver01/data/sn94060041/00542866731/1924012601/0041.xml":{"full_text":"Are You\nReady?\nReading the signs, they plainly indicate that the busi\nness depression is permanently behind us.\nBusiness in general assumes a decidedly move opto\nmistic outlook, and the business man with vision is already\ncarefully laying his plans for the business revival that is\nupon us.\nOne of the first and most important actions should be\nyour association with the BANK that is in a position to\nbest serve your requirements from a financial and advis\nory standpoint.\nThis bank most cordially invites an interview' with\nany one considering the establishment of new' or additional\nbanking connections.\nAonfidence llever Aetrayed\nTUB UiTizENS National dank\n\nof Pocomoke City, Md.\nBANK HABIT\nSAVING HABIT\nPROSPERITY\nOLD AGE COMFORTS\nElijah J. Schoolfield, President. Colmore E. Byrd, Cashier.\nJ. C. Stevenson, Trust Officer\nNew Christmas Club\nIn line with serving our friends the public in all pos\nsible ways we have installed a complete Christmas Club for\nthe convenience of everybody.\nWeekly deposits (in amounts to suit) are made\nthrough the year. In early December the entire principal,\nincreased by interest, is paid back at a time when it is most\nwelcome.\nNo formality about joining. Just make the first small\npayment.\nYou will be agreeably surprised how fast the money\ngrows.\nSpeak to your friends and relatives about the Club.\nYou can all save at the same time.\nClub Now Open\nThe Accomack Banking Co., Inc.\nParksley and Bloxom, Va.\nPOWER\nthrill\ny\nBloxom Bros. Co.\nBloxom, Virginia\nJohn W. Duncan\n^Jewelep\nOnancock, Virginia\nNEAR EAST RELIEF\nAccomack County for the past\nthree years has had a quota of $3,\n360 (that is the, care of 66 orphans\nat $60 a year) in Virginia\u2019s effort to\nsave 5,000 of the orphans in the\nNear Ehst countries. In these three\nyears we have raised a total of $13,r\n420.39, $3,340.39 beyond our quoto.\nfor the three years, an average per\nI year of $4,473.\u20196. Last year we\n1 raised our largest amount (cash and\nI year of $4,473.46. Last year we\nfive months? until June 30, to make;\ngood for 1924 our quoto of $3,36d,\nonly a small part of which is in hand.\nDr. Robert E. Speer says \u201cI doubt;\nwhether any great relief underaking\nhas ever been carrid through with a\nlarger measure of efficiency or fn^-1\ngality.\u201d Dr. S. M. Calvert, who is:\nGeneral Secretary of the Federal;\nCouncil of churches, says, ihat he be\nlieves it to be the sacred duty of\nevery congregation and Sunday\nSchool to give an opportunity to its\nmembers to contribute to this great\nwork\nWhy is this appeal continued year\nafter year? Because young orphans\ncannot be abandoned. It is the dis\nposition of America to \u201csee a job\nthrough.\u201d To abandon these little'\nchildren is unthinkable. This N. E.\nR. work provides the largest mis(-!\nsionary opportunity that has ever;\ncome to the American people in\nmoulding the lives of so many chil\nI dren, inspiring them with American\nIdeals and Christian principles. These\ni children may determine the future\n[destiny of the Near East.\nI Henry VanDylce in \"By Radio to:\nAmerica\u2019s Heart,\u201d says, \u201cInto the\nbright mirth of our sheltered homes, j\ni into the peaceful murmur of our\ncountry\u2019s prosperous life, there j\ncomes a strange and piercing cry\u2014a1\nsound of many voices moaning, wail\nI ing, and lamenting\u2014broken men,\noutraged women and bewildered chib\ndren,thousands, yes, myriads of suf\nfering souls in wounded, starving\nbodies, crying Help! Help!\nThese are the exiles of Christ in\nthe Near East, driven forth by the\nTurks to wander and perish. You\ncan he:y them crying if your heart\nis tuned to the key of humanity.\u201d.\nHe concludes with this, \u201cHow near is\nthe Near East to us? That depends:\nupon how near we are to Christ.\u201d\nj May we, as in the past, depend\nupon the various organizations of'\nour county \u201cto listen in\u2019\u2019 and catch\nithe appealing Call coming from the\n\u25a0fifty-six homeless orphans depending!\nupon Accomack County for their;\ncare? Let us say (with Kate Don-;\nglas Wiggin) in generous gifts of;\nmoney sent to our county treasurer j\nfor Near East Relief funds, Mr. D.!\nj H. Wessells, Keller, during\u2018the next\nfew weeks:\nMy latch is on the string ta|-night,\nThe hearth fire is aglow;\nI seem to hear swift passing feet,\nThe Christ Child in the snow.\nMy heart is open wide to-night,\n!For stranger, kith or kin,\nI would not close a single door\nWhere Christ may enter in.\nFairy M. White,\nChairman Accomack County\nNear East Relief.\nKeller, Va., Jan. 15, 10\u201924.\nIN MEMORIAM\nIn sad but loving remembrance of\nour darling baby, Marguerite Mar\nshall, who died January 17th, 1923,\njust one year ago, aged two years.\nIn a little snow white casket,\nResting sweetly among the flowers\nLies our darling little Marguerite,\nWho such a little while was ours.\nj Beneath this stone in soft repose,\nIs laid a mother's dearest pride,\nA flower that scarce had waked in\nlife,\nAnd light and beauty ere it died.\nThe roses, the fairest and sweetest,\nAnd the one we most cherished and!\nloved,\nIs the kind that God wants in His\ngarden,\nSo He transplanted our baby above.\nGone to a fairer land\nOf pleasure and love\nTo join the bright land\nOf angels above.\nBy Mama and Papa\nMr. and Mrs. Sollie Marshall\nIN MEMORIAM\nIn sad but loving remembrance of\nmy wife, Annie, who passed away\nthis January three years ago.\nThis months recalls sad memories\nOf the one I laid to rest,\nAnd those who still remember her\nAre the ones who loved her best.\nFrom our chain this link has fallen,\nIn the East the stars have set,\nBut engraved on memory\u2019s tablet\nIs the name I\u2019ll ne\u2019er forget.\nBy her Husband,\nArthur Killmon\nI have only your memory, dear\nmother,\nTo remember my whole life through,\nAnd that is one I never will forget,\nFor I will always think of you.\nBy her Daughter, Gertrude j\nj\nI We carry men\u2019s and boys\u2019 riding\nI pants and leggings.\nWatts Brothers,\ni Parksley, Va.\nPublic Auction\nOF VALUABLE\nPersonal Property\nThe undersigned owner, having de\ncided to reduce his farming opera\ntions will sell at public auction to the\nhighest bidder at his farm, now occu\npied by him near\nNEW CHURCH. VIRGINIA\nTuesday, February 5, 19241\nBeginning at 10 a. m.\nthe following described personal prop\nerty: One 2 horse sod cutter, 1 three\nhorse sod cutter, 1 Tiger transplanter,\n2 Aspinwall potato planters,' 1 Iron\nAge potato planter, 1 three row Mc\nWhorter fertilizer sower, 1 four row\npotato marker, 1 two horse lime and\nfertilizer sower, 1 four row drv Beetle\nDuster, 1 two horse, 6-row wet spray\ner i Standard mowing machine, 1\nhay kicker 1 hay rake, lweeder, 1\nJohn Deere riding cultivator, 1 Iron\nAge riding cultivator, 1 iron drag,\n7 ft., 1 8-ft. iron drag, 3 double horse\nwagons, 2. horse carts. 1 No. 19 Oliver\nChilled plow, 1 No. 19 John Deere\nplow, 1 No. 37 Lynchburg plow, 7\nwalking cultivators, 2 seed drags, 3\nsingle Farmer\u2019s Friend plows, 1 single\nClipper plow, 125 barrels No. 2 Irish\nCobblers, 125 8-ft cypress potato bed\nframes with glass, 100 6-ft. frames\nwith glass, 3 pairs mules weighing\nfrom 1,000 to 1,300 pounds each, 1\niozen single trees, 4 pieces cypress,\nl inches wide and 16 ft. long, 6 sweet\npotato rakes, 1 vine cutter wheel, 5\njoxes potato bed glass, 8 16-inch disc\nwheels, 6 hay forks, 4 rows wire\n\u2019once, 1 pump jack, 500 feet of pump\npipes with hydrants attached 15\nstacks fodder, 400 barrels com, 200\nnarrels No. 1 Irish Cobblers; harness\nind other things too numerous to\nnention.\nTERMS OF SALE\nFor all sums under $50 cash will\n>e required. For all sums over $50 the\npurchaser will be required to execute\nnegotiable note payable July 15th,\nL924, with interest from maturity\nwith approved security.\nAll of this property is in excellent\n\u2022ondition and will positively be sold\nis I have no use for same.\nIf the weather does not permit\ntolding sale on the above named date,\nsale will be held next day at same\nime and place. This will be one of\nhe largest personal property sales\n!ver held on the Eastern Shore of\n/irginia.\nFor further particulars see posters\nnr apply to Turlington Doughty,\nittomeys, or to the undersigned.\nASA T. HICKMAN. Owner.\nFAMILIES OF WORKERS\nWANTED AT HOPEWELL\nLarge Plant Employs All\nMembers of Family.\nHOFBWBLis TA.\u2014A large num\nber of families from various parts\nof the leuth art movlag hflfs to\nwork la tho plant of the Tubtze\nCompany, and tho etty ha\u00ab takes on\na busy. prooporono air.\n\u2018Yeung women and men who have\ntoo* thrown oat of employment by\nthe closing down of plants la other\nsootlono hare found employment\nhere Alee many farmers, hit by\ncrop looooo. aro bringing their fam\nilioo to Hopewell.\nTho Tnblse plant makes artificial\nsilk from a ootton base, and a large\nnmaber of boyo. girls and wemea are\nemployed ia tho rariouo prooeoees.\nThe work Is light aad pleasant, and\nworker* qulekly become expert.\nGood wagoo are earned while learn\ning and adranoemont is rapid.\nTho Tublno plant is one of the\nfinest and most modern In the South.\nThere is no lint or dust and sani\ntary conditions are of the best.\nBoth plant and etty hare an an\nusually high health record.\nHopewell has all modern conve\nniences. Houses and eottagea may\nbo had near tho plant at efceap\nrentals and living costs are low.\nTho oompany still bas a limited\nnumber of positions for girls and\nbeys, but entire families having\nseveral workers are especially need\ned\nThose interested should write at\nease to the Tubize Artificial Silk\nCo.. Hopewell. Va.. for full partie\nulara. The number of those In the\nfajnily wanting employment should\nbe mentioned.\u2014Adv.\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nCommissioner\u2019s Office,\nAccomac Court House, Va.\nJanuary 17th, 1924\nro the creditors of William H. Ma\nson, deceased, of Rue, Va.\nYou are hereby notified that at the\nrequest of the personal representa\ntive of said decedent, I have appoint\nid Monday the 4th day of February,\n1924, at my said office for receiving\nproof of all debts and demands\nagainst said decedent at which time\nyou will attend and present same.\nGiven under my hand this 17th day\nJanuary, 1924.\nJames C. Melson,\nCommissioner of Accounts.\nYou want to sell property see me\nYou want to buy property see me\nYou want to borrow money see me\nYou want to loan money see me\nYou want to rent property see me\nYou want to let property see me\nS. J. LOGAN\nBroker in Real Estate, Loans and\nInvestments\nGAPE CHARLES, VA\nP. 0. Box 6\nMarvelous Record Made by Studebaker Big-Six\n475,000 Miles\n____\nIn Everyday Service\nASSOCIATED TRANSIT CO., Inc.\nCONTRACT CARRIERS\nStudebaker Corporation of America,\n1250 So. Figueroa Street,\nLos Angeles, California.\nGentlemen:\nLos Angeles, Cal., Dec. 23, 1923\nStudebaker Big Six Touring Car, 1919 Model, Motor No. 7248, Serial No. 290,210 was\npurchased by this firm on Oct. 27th, 1920, and has been in our service for past three\nyears making two round trips daily hauling newspaper for the Los Angeles Times and\nLos Angeles Evening Express to Santa Barbara and intermediate points. The daily\nmileag'e for six days in the week was in excess of four hundred miles, the seventh day\nit made only one round trip, of two hundred and twenty-five miles.\nAccording to our records, this car, while in our possession traveled in excess of four\nhundred thousand (400,000) miles; averaged approximately fourteen miles to the gallon\nof gasoline; and better than twenty thousand miles on a set of tires.\nThe car was in active service when turned over to you and has now been replaced\nwith a 1924 Studebaker Big Six.\nYours very truly,\nAssociated Transit Co., Inc.\nBy- President\nSubscribed and sworn to before me this 23rd day.of December, 1923.\nBenj. Wood,\nNotary Public in and for the County of Ventura, California.\nStudebaker Corporation,\n1250 S. Figueroa St.\nLos Angeles, Calif.\nGentlemen:\nSimi, Calif., Dec. 22,1923\nStudebaker Big Six Touring Car, 1919 Model, Motor No. 7248, Series 290,210, was\npurchased by me on June 13, 1918, and was used by me up to Oct. 27, 1920, during\nwhich time I drove the car a little over 94,000 miles, the same being used in California,\nOregon, Washington, Wyoming, Nevada, Arizona and old Mexico, under all kinds of\nroads as well as climatic conditions.\nAccording to my records the car averaged 14 miles per gallon of gasoline, and\napproximately 1,000 miles per gallon of oil.\nYours very truly,\nSubscribed and sworn to before me this 22nd\nday of December, 1923.\nL. I. Dinsmore\u201e\nNotary Public in and for the County of Ventura, California.\nFenton Norman.\nThis veteran car has just reached New York City from Los Angeles. It bucked\nthe desert, conquered the snow and ice mountain passes, won its way through the quag\nmire of the middle Western roads and came all the way from coast to coast without\nroad delay except two punctui es. The car carries the orginal body, motor transmission\nand rear axle assemblies. No complete unit has ever been replaced. The mileage is\nequal to twenty trips around the world and it is a World\u2019s record for distance for any\nkind of automobile. Come in and we will give full particulars and show you the im\nprovements of the new models over the old.\nOnley Garage\nOnley, Virginia\nPublic Auction\nof a Carload of\nHorses and Mules\na\nAt the Stables of Calvin E Townsend\nIN POCOMOKE CITY, MD.\nSaturday, January 26, 1924;\nAt 1 o\u2019clock p. m.\nThis stock was selected especially\nfor the market.. They are all broke\nand ready for use, and will weigh\nfrom 800 to 1400 pounds. This is a\ngood opportunity for anyone needing\nhorses or mules as they are excep\ntionally good animals. They can be\ninspected on Friday preceding sale\ndate. Sale will take place rain or\nshine.\nTERMS OF SALE\nFour months credit will be given,\nthe purchaser to give bankable note\nwith approved security.\nFRANK BOWLER\nTHE BEST WAY\nTO GET YOUR IRON\nPHYSICIANS have prescribed\nGude\u2019s Pepto-Mangan for 30\nyears because of its supply of\niron. They found that it was readily\nabsorbed, did not irritate the stom\nach and quickly toned and strength\nened the system. At your drug\ngist\u2019s, in both liquid and tablets.\nFree Trial Tablets 3,\u00b0h\u00abuh.tSni\nvalue of Gude\u2019a Pepto-Mangan, write today\nfor generous Trial Package of Tablets. Send\nno money \u2014*ju\u00bbt name and address to\nM. J. Breitenbach Co., 63 \"Warren St., N. Y.\nGude\u2019s\nPepto-Mangan\nTonic and Blood Enricher\nQuality\nis a much abused word, but NOT when applied to\nRoyster\u2019s\nFertilizers\nQUALITY is remembered long after PRICE is for\ngotten. If you have not already made arrangements for\nyour needs, we suggest you do so promptly.\nConsult our nearest agent or write direct to\nF. S. Royster Guano Company\n1606-1613 Munsey Building\nBaltimore, Maryland\nLIFE INSURANCE\nThe Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance Company of Milwaukee\nissues up-to-date policy contracts for the protection of home, wife\nand children at lowest net cost.\nYou are cordially invited to ask information of agents concern\ning the low cost and attractive policies of the Northwestern.\nSPENCER F. ROGERS, Agent\nONANCOCK, VIRGINIA\nSubscribe for the Enterprise.","height":"26672","width":"20036"}}
